Welcome to The Daily Courant, your afternoon dispatch featuring Puck=E2=80=
=99s best new
reporting.

=C2=A0

First up today, William D. Cohan chronicles the earlyish, heady days of Wal=
l Street=E2=80=99s embrace of artificial intelligence, and chats with a you=
ng founder at the center of it all. Of course, questions are emerging: Will=
 rapid A.I. advancements improve the work-life balance of junior bankers, o=
r replace them entirely?

=C2=A0

Plus, below the fold: Leigh Ann Caldwell, Puck=E2=80=99s chief Washington c=
orrespondent, identifies the stress cracks in the G.O.P.=E2=80=99s outwardl=
y ebullient coalition. Dylan Byers assesses CNN=E2=80=99s growing pains as =
Mark Thompson=E2=80=99s digital transformation kicks off. Marion Maneker po=
nders Sotheby=E2=80=99s year-end emphasis on their $1 billion real estate p=
ortfolio. Julie Davich investigates the art
world=E2=80=99s revived fascination with the late Louise Nevelson. And Sara=
h Shapiro offers her expert assessment of the most telling pre-Valentine=E2=
=80=99s Day retail trends.=C2=A0=C2=A0

Meanwhile, on the pods: John Heilemann hosts communications strategist Jenn=
ifer Palmieri on Impolitic to break down the A.O.C.=E2=80=93M.T.G. politica=
l horseshoe theory. On The Varsity, John
Ourand reconnects with Michael Nathanson to evaluate ESPN=E2=80=99s streami=
ng strategy and Netflix=E2=80=99s potential UFC bid. And on The Powers That=
 Be, Jon Kelly and Peter Hamby check the timeline for CNN=E2=80=99s digital=
 overhaul and debate why news orgs like the Times are toning down their Tru=
mp coverage.

